          "body": "The four living creatures (chay, vv. 5–14; identified as cherubim in 10:1–22) are the most formally complex element of the vision. Their fourfold faces — man, lion, ox, eagle (v. 10) — have generated centuries of interpretation. Irenaeus applied them to the four Gospels; John's Apocalypse places them around the throne (Revelation 4:6–8); early iconography standardized the association with Matthew (man), Mark (lion), Luke (ox), and John (eagle). But in Ezekiel's immediate context, the four faces represent the four supreme orders of creation: man (the image-bearer and sovereign of creation), lion (king of wild animals), ox (king of domestic and agricultural animals), eagle (king of birds). Together, the fourfold creature-form declares that God's throne is attended by all that creation has produced at its most excellent and powerful. Every created order serves the Creator. The creatures also move without turning (vv. 9, 12), always going straight ahead — a visual metaphor for absolute moral directness and the undeviating execution of the divine will."
